INSERT INTO `content_props` VALUES ('100', '<p><strong>Day 1: Siem Reap </strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many direct flies to Siem Reap, Cambodia via Bangkok, Singapore, Malaysia and other destinations. According to your arrival time, our guide will be pleased to give you some suggestions what to do on your first day or afternoon in Siem Reap. In the evening followed by a welcome dinner for our first night in Cambodia. Meals: D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 2: Great Lake </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will visit Roluos group, a collection of monuments representing the remains of Hariharalaya, the first major capital of the Angkorian-era Khmer Empire.<br /> Then on to the fishermen’s village of Kompong Phluk<strong>, </strong>As we will arrive at the village at about Noon, we will enjoy a nice lunch from fresh local fish, shrimps and vegetables prepared by the local family in the village. It is a easy way to explore the village by walking and small canoes, paddle by villagers, will take you deep into the dense flooded forest during the wet season, it is a plenty of Kodak moment are awaiting for us today. Late afternoon, we will get on our local boat to other floating village. End of the day we will enjoy sunset view on Phnom Krom hilltop overview of Great Lake in Southeast-Asia. Meals: B, L, Dinner with traditional Dance Show</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 3-4: Angkor </strong></p>\r\n<p>Angkor covered an area about 402 Square Km and during this trip we will have two full days to explore this ancient capital. Our expert guide will chose the good timing to explore the main Angkor Complex include sunrise and sunset, Angkor Thom, Angkor Wat included small and grand circle of Angkor Area are all amazing temples to visit as well as we also drive through countryside to visit Kbal Spean and Banteay Srei temple were built from the pink sandstone. During our visit Angkor we also still have chance to visit many NGOs supported and even also children hospital and Landmine museum. Most of the restaurants that we will use for our lunches and dinners are NGOs training restaurants where students of the School of Hotel and Tourism will gain valuable experience through serving foods to us. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 5: Koh Ker &amp; Beng Melea temple </strong></p>\r\n<p>Koh Ker was the capital city of the Khmer Empire during hardly two decades (928-944) during the reign of Jayavarman IV. The main ruins at Koh Ker consist of an impressive seven-storey sandstone pyramid (Prasat Thom). It is believed that over 80 ruins lie in this area. Then, a one-hour drive will take us to Beng Melea is completely ruined and largely overrun by vegetation. Our last stop today near the village of Kompong Kdei to seePhra Phutthos an old bridge of the Angkorean Era. Meals: B, L</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 6: Banteay Chhmar &amp; Trapeang Thmor </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will drive to the west of Siem Reap city to Banteay Chhmar temple was built during the reign of the king Jayavarman VII for Mahayana Buddhism. Then we will continue to Trapeang Thmor reservoir, it is a largest reservoir in the country and it built during the Khmer Rouge regime (1975-1979). There are a lot of people have been moved to built this reservoir and they killed them. It is one of the historical site of Khmer Rouge in the country. Meals: B, L</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 7: Phnom Kulen &amp; Anlong Veng </strong></p>\r\n<p>We drive to northeast of Siem Reap to the <strong>Phnom Kulen</strong>(Lychee Mountain), a sandstone plateau considered sacred by the Khmers. There, you will see the ancient sculptures on the riverbed, a pagoda which homes the biggest reclining Buddha of the country, carved in the rock. The hike will continue towards the 30 meters high waterfalls. We will continue our drive to the north on a countryside road and trip through the jungle we will arrive at <strong>Anlong Veng</strong><strong>,</strong> sadly famous for having been the last Khmer Rouge stronghold. Tonight we will share our experience with a local homestay in one of the former Khmer Rouge family. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 8: Historical site of Khmer Rouge </strong></p>\r\n<p>After breakfast with our host family then, we will explore Anlong Veng and its most popular destination, Oh Chit, an artificial lake initially built as a moat by Ta Mok for his house. Then we will drive up the Dong Rek hill to visit Pol Pot’s grave as well as his house. It is a nice market between Cambodia and Thailand border to visit and having lunch with some local dishes in this market. Late afternoon, we will drive to Trapeang Prasat village to visit Trapeang Prasat temple was built during Khmer empire. Then return to our family homestay. Tonight we will arrange a small party to enjoy some rice wine and local special dishes. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 9: Preah Vihear </strong></p>\r\n<p>Goodbye to our family then continue our journey to <strong>Preah Vihear</strong>. The temple dominates the plain from its prominent position in the Dong Rek Mountains, which straddle the Thai border, at an altitude of more than 700 m. Be that as it may, the stunning view onto the surrounding which, on a clear day, reach all the way to Phnom Kulen to the west and the intersection of the Lao, Thai and Cambodian borders to the east, will reward us for our effort. We will have plenty of time to visit the temple and the area and enjoy the beautiful sunset on the top of the hill. Accommodation at Environment House (Need to check if it is still possible and also ask to arrange dinner or we should prepare dinner by ourselves. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 10: Tbeng Meanchey </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will visit <strong>sunrise from the top</strong>. Then, we drive to our next destination. We will pass through the deciduous dipterocarp forest and grassland mosaic of the Northern Plains of Cambodia, home of some of the rarest bird species of South-east Asia, such as some Ibis (like the Giant Ibis, the Cambodia’s national bird), Vultures and Ducks; most of them are endangered. We will stop en route for lunch. We will arrive at our destination, the temples of <strong>Preah Khan</strong>, also know as Prasat Bakan. This is one of the most remote temple of Cambodia and when exploring the temples you will have a real feel of being lost in the middle of nowhere.<br /> Then, we will drive back to the small provincial city of Tbeng Meancheay where we will arrive in the evening. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p>Accommodation at Phrum Meas Guesthouse or Camping if it is possible</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 11: Joom Noon Silk Project</strong></p>\r\n<p>We will visit <strong>Joom Noon Silk Project</strong>. The Joom Noon Silk project is a local initiative to help rehabilitate people with disabilities and which produce some of the country’s finest silk. Today we will spend one more night in this rural village and you can have time to explore more temples and surrounding area or relaxing in the village by visiting some local school. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p>Maybe book local family to cook for the group</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 12: Ratanakiri </strong></p>\r\n<p>Early morning we will leave Tbeng Meanchey, Preah Vihear and motorcyclists in particular rave about the off-road opportunities and en route to Thalaborivath, Stung Treng then continue drive to Ratanakiri. It is a new route in Cambodia which no way to travel from Preah Vihear to Stung Treng since French colonial in Cambodia. It is quite a spirit adventure of this route, Meals: B, L, D <strong><br /> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 13: Beung Yeak Loam         </strong></p>\r\n<p>Breakfast at the hotel, then we will go to visit Ka Chanh Waterfall and Cha Ong Waterfall, today we will also have chance to explore some Khmer tribal people live in small town (Reung Sei Village, Pnorng Village and other many villages)</p>\r\n<p>Afternoon, we will swim at Beung Yeak Loam (Is the natural lake, which locates at the middle of the mountain in Yeak Loam Commune, and there are two harbours protruded to the above of the water for tourists to view the scenery and birds that are swimming along the stretch of the forest surrounding the lake). Meals: B, L</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 14: Preah Rumkel Community Based Ecotourism   </strong></p>\r\n<p>The province of Stung Treng marks Cambodia\'s northern border with Laos and the point where the Mekong river enters Cambodia after swirling its way around the 4,000 Islands of southern Laos. Stung Treng doesn\'t sit on the bank of the Mekong, but rather on the southern bank of the San River which flows into the far larger Mekong about a kilometre west of town. Upon arrival in Stung Streng province then we will continue our journey to Preah Rumkel community based ecotourism with an explosion of wildlife rivalled only by that of the Amazon, the Ramsar Wetlands are one of Cambodia’s richest biodiversity hotspots. Explore flooded forests and magnificent waterfalls, take an energising mountain hike and see rare Mekong River dolphins before trying traditional rice wine at a friendly homestay. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p>O’Svay (Homestay)</p>\r\n<p>Mr. Kong Vuthy, Chief of Community,</p>\r\n<p>Tel: +855-11-256-092 / +855-17-828-632</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Preah Rumkel Community Based Ecotourism</p>\r\n<p>Poy Vanna, Community Committee Member</p>\r\n<p>Tel: +855-11-899-891 (Khmer Speaking)</p>\r\n<p>+855-12-968-788 (Khmer and English)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 15: Kratie </strong></p>\r\n<p>We Continue by boat from Preah Rumkel village to O’Svay village. We will explore a forest trail and a boat trip through the Ramsar Wetlands (slow boat = 3-4hrs) and visit the tiny community of Veun Sien then Stop at Koh Khao Din (from here, cyclists can disembark and ride the 15km back to town) before continuing back to Stung Treng town.</p>\r\n<p>Then we will continue to the province of Kratie, this city is quite well-preserved and still has some good examples of chophouses architecture as well as some old Khmer wooden house but is mostly the most famous resident of this mighty waterway is the Mekong River dolphin. This afternoon we will enjoy boat trip to see dolphin and continue to the spectacular scenery of the whole area is best viewed from the top of Sambok Mountain, where a lesson in Buddhism awaits. On the way back to our homestay we will stop to watch and taste as families prepare local delicacies krolan (bamboo sticky rice) and nem (pickled raw fish wrapped in banana leaves) at Thma Kreae village for market. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p> Kampi</p>\r\n<p>Tel: +855-97-586-288 (Community Based Tourism)</p>\r\n<p>Tel: +855-12-358-305 (Tourist Police)</p>\r\n<p>(Khmer Speaking)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day16: 100 Pillars Pagoda</strong></p>\r\n<p>We will leave Kampi to the north to reach Sambour town and continue to the original Wat Sarsar Mouy Roy (‘100 Pillars Pagoda’) is three wooden pillars. Destroyed by Pol Pot’s forces in the 1970s, this 16th century edifice has since been restored to its former glory. Then take a boat to Koh Phdao, one of the most beautiful islands in the Mekong, try your hand at village life. Afterwards, enjoy a traditional dance performance; join a Khmer cooking lesson or volunteer to teach English. Don’t miss the Mekong Turtle Conservation Centre, where you can see tiny turtle hatchlings. We will overnight on this island and take part in village life. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 17: Mondulkiri</strong></p>\r\n<p>We will travel to the province of Mondulkiri. Mondul Kiri means “meeting of the hills” a suitable name for such a hilly province. At an elevation of 800m, it is chilly at night; almost half the 30,000 inhabitants are from the Phnong minority group with the Chunchiet people making up most of the remaining population.</p>\r\n<p>There is no activities are plannedin this afternoon so you can choose between the many possibilities offered by the area. You will be able to explore the local market where many of the Phnong people from the nearby villages are coming to trade with the distinctive baskets they carry on their back. You will also be able to visit some of the hill tribes’ villages and assist to a minority cultural show or make an excursion to a waterfall among the 100 present in this area. The most famous is Boos Ra Waterfall, the biggest in Cambodia, 35 km from town. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 18: Elephant Trekking </strong></p>\r\n<p>Today we will enjoy an elephant trek from one of the minority ethnic villages. It will give you the opportunity to explore surrounding jungle, habitat and ethnic minority villages and will be for sure a memorable experience. These trekking are an important income based for the villagers. Meals: B, L</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 19: Phnom Penh </strong></p>\r\n<p>Our journey will continue to the village of Snoul, which is famous for its fruits cultivation. This town has a rather large market where we will stop and to taste some of their delicious fruits. We will pass along many rubber plantations including the biggest one of the country at Chhup. We will reach to Phnom Penh in the afternoon then you still have time to relax before enjoy sunset with a boat ride along the Tonle Sap river overview of Phnom Penh is charming city with the French colonial building style and the evening we will enjoy a drink on the FCC rooftop. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 20: Royal Palace  </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will visit the <strong>Royal Palace</strong> and<strong>Silver Pagoda</strong>. This amazing place, which floor is covered with 5000 silver plates, houses the Preah Keo or emerald Buddha, made of Baccarat crystal. In front stands a 90 kg golden Buddha studded with 9584 diamonds. After this, we will walk about 10 minutes to the <strong>National Museum</strong>. Built around a central courtyard, the galleries, arranged chronologically, present a collection of Khmer art, mostly sculptures. In the afternoon, we will drive to the <strong>Choeng Ek killing fields</strong> and the <strong>Tuol Sleng genocide Museum</strong> - a mass gravesite and a former high school converted to a detention and torture centre by the Khmers Rouges when they came to power in 1975. Choeung Ek also serves as a memorial to those killed under the Khmers Rouges rule. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 21: End of tour </strong></p>\r\n<p>The tour end after breakfast, you will have free time to explore central town or relax at the hotel before flight out. There are international flights to Bangkok or Vietnam and many other Asian destinations. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Included:</strong><br /> - Accommodation on twin sharing basis and meals as stated in the itinerary <br /> - Entrance fees and sightseeing tours by tuktuk, van, Jeep &amp; 4WD car <br /> - An experienced English-speaking local leader<br /> - One week Angkor pass<br /> - The services of a local guide at some part of the trip  </p>\r\n<p><strong>Not included:</strong><br /> - Personal travel insurance (compulsory!)<br /> - International flight , airport taxes &amp; excess baggage charges<br /> - Visa &amp; visa fees, passeport &amp; vaccination charges<br /> - Arrival &amp; departure transfers<br /> - Departure tax<br /> - All optional tours &amp; activities during free time<br /> - Expenditure of a personal nature, such as souvenir, laundry, postage, phone calls, etc……<br /> - Drinks &amp; tips<br /> - Other meals not mentioned in the itinerary</p>', null);
