INSERT INTO `content_props` VALUES ('138', '<p><strong>Day 1: Siem Reap  </strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many direct flies to Siem Reap, Cambodia via Bangkok, Singapore, Malaysia and other destinations. According to your arrival time, our guide will be pleased to give you some suggestions what to do on your first day or afternoon in Siem Reap. In the evening followed by a welcome dinner for our first night in Cambodia. Meals: D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 2-3-4: Angkor </strong></p>\r\n<p>Angkor covered an area about 402 Square Km and during this trip we will have three full days to explore this ancient capital. Our expert guide will chose the good timing to explore the main Angkor Complex include sunrise and sunset, Angkor Thom, Angkor Wat included small and grand circle of Angkor Area are all amazing temples to visit as well as we also drive through countryside to visit Kbal Spean and Banteay Srei temple were built from the pink sandstone. During our visit Angkor we also still have chance to visit many NGOs supported and even also children hospital and Landmine museum. Most of the restaurants that we will use for our lunches and dinners are NGOs training restaurants where students of the School of Hotel and Tourism will gain valuable experience through serving foods to us. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 5: Phnon Penh </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will take a regular speedboat departing from Siem Reap at 7:00 am. The boat will first navigate along the river before enter into the <strong>Tonle Sap lake</strong>, the biggest lake of Southeast Asia. This is a very scenic and picturesque journey, you will enjoy the wonderful landscape, passing through the flooded forest and the floating villages and learn about the daily life on the lake and along the river. This marvellous journey lasts about 6 hours during the wet season but can be considerably longer in the dry season due to low water. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 6: Royal Palace  </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will visit the <strong>Royal Palace</strong> and<strong>Silver Pagoda</strong>. This amazing place, which floor is covered with 5000 silver plates, houses the Preah Keo or emerald Buddha, made of Baccarat crystal. In front stands a 90 kg golden Buddha studded with 9584 diamonds. After this, we will walk about 10 minutes to the <strong>National Museum</strong>. Built around a central courtyard, the galleries, arranged chronologically, present a collection of Khmer art, mostly sculptures. In the afternoon, we will drive to the <strong>Choeng Ek killing fields</strong> and the <strong>Tuol Sleng genocide Museum</strong> - a mass gravesite and a former high school converted to a detention and torture centre by the Khmers Rouges when they came to power in 1975. Choeung Ek also serves as a memorial to those killed under the Khmers Rouges rule. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 7: Kompong Cham</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our journey today will reach Kampong Cham, the third largest town of Cambodia, located on the banks of the mighty Mekong River, North of Phnom Penh. We will visit Phnom Pros and Phnom Srei (“Man and Woman Hill”). In the afternoon we will ride bicycles to theKoh Pean Island to meet children of these poor villages and give them some school supplies, toothbrushes, food and little joy. On the way, you will be able to see the activities of the locals at the paddy field and inside the village. This type of real life experience in Cambodia will allow you to share some vibrant moments with people. During the dry season, we will reach the island by crossing the bamboo bridge (which is rebuilt every year) and during the wet season, a ferry will take us to other side. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 8: Mondulkiri</strong></p>\r\n<p>We will travel to the province of Mondulkiri. The journey will take around five hours. We will pass along many rubber plantations including the biggest one of the country at Chhup. Our journey will continue to the village of Snoul, which is famous for its fruits cultivation. This town has a rather large market where we will stop for lunch and to taste some of their delicious fruits. On arrival at Sen Monorom, the quiet provincial capital city of Mondulkiri. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 9: Elephant Trekking </strong></p>\r\n<p>Mondul Kiri means “meeting of the hills” a suitable name for such a hilly province. At an elevation of 800m, it is chilly at night; almost half the 30,000 inhabitants are from the Phnong minority group with the Chunchiet people making up most of the remaining population. <br /> Today we will enjoy an elephant trek from one of the minority ethnic villages. It will give you the opportunity to explore surrounding jungle, habitat and ethnic minority villages and will be for sure a memorable experience. These trekking are an important income based for the villagers. Meals: B, L</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 10: Free at Leisure </strong></p>\r\n<p>Today no activities are plannedso you can choose between the many possibilities offered by the area. You will be able to explore the local market where many of the Phnong people from the nearby villages are coming to trade with the distinctive baskets they carry on their back. You will also be able to visit some of the hill tribes’ villages and assist to a minority cultural show or make an excursion to a waterfall among the 100 present in this area. The most famous is Boos Ra Waterfall, the biggest in Cambodia, 35 km from town. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 11: Ratanakiri </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will say goodbye and travel to the province of Kratie, this city is quite well-preserved and still has some good examples of chophouses architecture as well as some old Khmer wooden house but is mostly the best place in Cambodia to see the freshwater Irrawady dolphins. After a boat trip onto the Mekong River then we will continue to the province of Ratanakiri. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 12: Beung Yeak Loam          </strong></p>\r\n<p>Breakfast at the hotel, then we will go to visit Ka Chanh Waterfall and Cha Ong Waterfall, afternoon, we will swim at Beung Yeak Loam (Is the natural lake, which locates at the middle of the mountain in Yeak Loam Commune, and there are two harbours protruded to the above of the water for tourists to view the scenery and birds that are swimming along the stretch of the forest surrounding the lake), today we will also have chance to explore some Khmer tribal people live in small town (Reung Sei Village, Pnorng Village and other many villages). Meals: B, L</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 13: Free at Leisure </strong></p>\r\n<p>Today we will have another full day to explore this mountain province, there are no activities plan for today so you can relax at the hotel or rent a motorbike or bicycles to explore the market and its surrounding area. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 14: Preah Rumkel Community Based Ecotourism   </strong></p>\r\n<p>The province of Stung Treng marks Cambodia\'s northern border with Laos and the point where the Mekong river enters Cambodia after swirling its way around the 4,000 Islands of southern Laos. Stung Treng doesn\'t sit on the bank of the Mekong, but rather on the southern bank of the San River which flows into the far larger Mekong about a kilometre west of town. Upon arrival in Stung Streng province then we will continue our journey to Preah Rumkel community based ecotourism with an explosion of wildlife rivalled only by that of the Amazon, the Ramsar Wetlands are one of Cambodia’s richest biodiversity hotspots. Explore flooded forests and magnificent waterfalls, take an energising mountain hike and see rare Mekong River dolphins before trying traditional rice wine at a friendly homestay. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p>O’Svay (Homestay)</p>\r\n<p>Mr. Kong Vuthy, Chief of Community,</p>\r\n<p>Tel: +855-11-256-092 / +855-17-828-632</p>\r\n<p>Preah Rumkel Community Based Ecotourism</p>\r\n<p>Poy Vanna, Community Committee Member</p>\r\n<p>Tel: +855-11-899-891 (Khmer Speaking)</p>\r\n<p>+855-12-968-788 (Khmer and English)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 15: Stung Treng</strong></p>\r\n<p>We Continue by boat from Preah Rumkel village to O’Svay village. We will explore a forest trail and a boat trip through the Ramsar Wetlands (slow boat = 3-4hrs) and visit the tiny community of Veun Sien then Stop at Koh Khao Din (from here, cyclists can disembark and ride the 15km back to town) before continuing back to Stung Treng town. If we still have time in the afternoon, Discover how silk is made at Mekong Blue mulberry farm and weaving centre and Sample delicacies such as nem (pickled raw fish wrapped in banana leaves) then continue to watch the sunset at Wat Thom Raing Sey. We will back to Stung Treng and dine at Le Tonle’ Tourism training center. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 16: Four Thousand Islands</strong></p>\r\n<p>Transfer to Dang Krolor then cross the border to Laos, we will reach Don Det Island by local slow boat. These famous 4000islands are representing the heaven on earth for backpacker travellers. After check-in we will have time to enjoy swim around the island or relax with a cheap cold Laos beers and Laos foods. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 17: Free at leisure </strong></p>\r\n<p>It is a relaxing day or you can rent a bicycle to enjoy around the Don Det island or cycle to following the old French wharf and along the old French railway line to the waterfalls. In the late afternoon, you can enjoy swimming with local villager around the 4000 islands as well as tubing along the river. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 18: Temple of Wat Phu</strong></p>\r\n<p>Today we will visit to waterfall of Tad Yeung and on the way take a look at the coffee and tea plantations. Then we will visit the sacred Khmer temple of Wat Phu. This was the easternmost border of the Khmer Empire during the Angkor period.</p>\r\n<p>Later in the afternoon we take a boat trip from Champasak to Don Daeng Island and overnight in the village of Hua Don Daeng at community guesthouse. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 19: Free at leisure    </strong></p>\r\n<p>Stretched out like an old croc sunning itself in the middle of the Mekong, Don Daeng is a little like an island that time forgot. The remains of a square-based brick prasat in the centre of the island and another, hiding under the sim at Wat Ban Boung Kham, suggest the island has been inhabited since Khmer times, at least. But the attraction of Don Daeng is more about just soaking up village life. Walking or cycling around the village you’ll find people refreshingly welcoming.</p>\r\n<p>Today is free at leisure till dinnertime arrange by the villager at community based. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 20: Pakse</strong></p>\r\n<p>Today we will take a boat trip back to Champasak and then drive to Pakse province and upon arrival you will have a half-day to explore the city and tonight we will enjoy a lovely farewell dinner in one of the local restaurant. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 21: End of tour </strong></p>\r\n<p>The tour end after breakfast, you will have free time to explore central town or relax at the hotel before flight out. There are international flights to Bangkok or Vietnam and many other Asian destinations. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Included:</strong><br /> - Accommodation on twin sharing basis and meals as stated in the itinerary <br /> - Entrance fees and sightseeing tours by tuktuk and private aircon vehicles<br /> - An experienced English-speaking local leader<br /> - The services of local guides at some sites<br /> - Elephant trek in Mondulkiri<br /> - Public bus from Phnom Penh to Kompong Cham<br /> - Transportation from Kompong Cham to Sen Monorom (Mondulkiri)<br /> - Transportation from Sen Monorom to Kratie<br /> - Public bus from Kratie to Phnom Penh<br /> - Boat trip in Kratie<br /> - Boat trip to Koh Dach (Phnom Penh)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Not included:</strong><br /> - Personal travel insurance (compulsory!)<br /> - International flight , airport taxes &amp; excess baggage charges<br /> - Visa &amp; visa fees, passeport &amp; vaccination charges<br /> - Arrival &amp; departure transfers<br /> - Departure tax<br /> - All optional tours &amp; activities during free time<br /> - Expenditure of a personal nature, such as souvenir, laundry, postage, phone calls, etc……<br /> - Drinks &amp; tips<br /> - Other meals not mentioned in the itinerary</p>', null);
