INSERT INTO `content_props` VALUES ('139', '<p><strong >Day 1: Siem Reap </strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many direct flies to Siem Reap, Cambodia via Bangkok, Singapore, Malaysia and other destinations. According to your arrival time, our guide will be pleased to give you some suggestions what to do on your first day or afternoon in Siem Reap. In the evening followed by a welcome dinner for our first night in Cambodia. Meals: D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 2: Roluos Group &amp; Great Lake Tonle Sap  </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will visit <strong>Roluos group</strong>, a collection of monuments representing the remains of Hariharalaya, the first major capital of the Angkorian-era Khmer Empire. Then we will take a boat cruise and canoe through the <strong>fishermen’s village of Kompong Phluk</strong><strong>among</strong>its houses on stilts. In the afternoon we will climb the <strong>Phnom Krom hil</strong><strong>l </strong>to visit the three old towers dedicated to Shiva, Vishnu and Brahma. Meals: B, L, Dinner with traditional show</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 3-4: Angkor </strong></p>\r\n<p>Angkor covered an area about 402 Square Km and during this trip we will have two full days to explore this ancient capital. Our expert guide will chose the good timing to explore the main Angkor Complex include sunrise and sunset, Angkor Thom, Angkor Wat included small and grand circle of Angkor Area are all amazing temples to visit as well as we also drive through countryside to visit Kbal Spean and Banteay Srei temple were built from the pink sandstone. During our visit Angkor we also still have chance to visit many NGOs supported and even also children hospital and Landmine museum. Most of the restaurants that we will use for our lunches and dinners are NGOs training restaurants where students of the School of Hotel and Tourism will gain valuable experience through serving foods to us. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 5: Phnon Penh </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will leave Siem Reap in the morning and stop near the village of Kompong Kdei to see an old bridge of the Angkorean Era, Phra Phutthos, better know as <strong>Kompong Kdei Bridge. </strong>Then, we will continue to <strong>Sambor Prei Kuk</strong> is the setting of the most impressive group of pre-Angkorian monuments anywhere in Cambodia. After the visit, we will drive to Phnom Penh capital. Meals: B, L, D (Picnic lunch around the temple)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 6: Phnom Penh </strong></p>\r\n<p>We will drive 15 km south of the city to Choeung Ek, a mass gravesite known to the locals as the <strong>Killing Fields</strong>after the popular movie of Roland Joffre. Then, we will drive back to the city center and visit the <strong>Tuol Sleng genocide museum</strong>. In the Afternoon, we will visit the<strong>Royal Palace</strong>and <strong>Silver Pagoda, National Museum</strong><strong>.</strong> Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 7: End of tour</strong></p>\r\n<p>The tour end after breakfast, you will have free time to explore central town or relax at the hotel before flight out. There are international flights to Bangkok or Vietnam and many other Asian destinations. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Service included:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Accommodation twin share basis with daily breakfast and all kind of tax</p>\r\n<p>An experienced English-speaking local guide</p>\r\n<p>All ground transportation as mention on the itinerary</p>\r\n<p>Sightseeing fee during guiding</p>\r\n<p>Meals as stated on the itinerary (B: Breakfast, L: Lunch, D: Dinner)</p>\r\n<p>Water during the tours</p>\r\n<p>Boat trip onto Tonle Sap Lake</p>\r\n<p>Apsara Theatre and Shadow puppet\'s show in Siem Reap</p>\r\n<p>Arrival &amp; Departure transfer</p>\r\n<p><strong>Service excluded:</strong></p>\r\n<p>All airfare, airport taxes and excess baggage charges</p>\r\n<p>All kind of own expenses</p>\r\n<p>Visa, Visa fee and vaccination charges</p>\r\n<p>Departure tax (25$)</p>\r\n<p>Personal travel insurance (compulsory)</p>\r\n<p>All optional tours &amp; activities during free time</p>\r\n<p>All beverages during the included meals</p>\r\n<p>Expenditure of a personal nature, such as souvenir, laundry, postage, phone calls</p>\r\n<p>Tips</p>', null);
