INSERT INTO `content_props` VALUES ('140', '<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><strong>Day 1: Phnom Penh</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many direct flies to Phnom Penh, Cambodia via Bangkok, Singapore, Vietnam, Malaysia and other destinations. According to your arrival time, our guide will be pleased to give you some suggestions what to do on your first day or afternoon in Phnom Penh. In the evening followed by a welcome dinner for our first night in Cambodia. Meals: D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 2-3: Rabbit Island</strong></p>\r\n<p>We will leave Phnom Penh to <strong>Kep</strong><strong>,</strong> famous for its seafood, especially fresh crab.<br /> Upon arrival, a thirty minutes boat cruise will take us on<strong>Rabbit Island</strong>, a lovely little island that sits offshore from Kep. This small island has two white sandy beaches with coconut trees and shallow waters. You can also walk along the beaches or inside the island through the beautiful forest hoping to see some giant bats, unless you are just dreaming of lying on a hammock with a good book and cocktail drink or to enjoy a refreshing swim in the crystal sea. We will accommodate with two nights wooden bungalow and BBQ seafood for our outstanding dinner along the quiet beach. Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 4-5: Sihanoukville </strong></p>\r\n<p>We resume our journey on the road which runs along the sea to Sihanoukville. This is Cambodia’s leading beach resort. There are white-sand beaches around the headland, unspoilt islands off the coast and the popular Khal Chhay waterfall near town. You will have a free afternoon to enjoy the beaches or explore the city. We will enjoy one day on the boat trip to Ream National Park was protected in 1993, inaugurated in March 1995 and encompasses 21,000 hectares of coastal area including sandy beaches, Mangrove forests, The Prek Tuk Sap estuary, off-shore coral reefs and two islands (Koh Thmie and Koh Seh). Meals: B, L, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 6: Phnom Penh </strong></p>\r\n<p>Leaving to Phnom Penh at around 2pm, we still have another half day to enjoy more beaches in Sihanoukville and we suggest to have lunch at <strong>Starfish Bakery Café</strong>from the Starfish Project which assists disabled families and individuals to becoming independent through housing, community and water projects. Meals: B</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 7: Killing Field &amp; S21</strong></p>\r\n<p>We will drive about 16 kilometers to the Choeng Ek killing fields and the Tuol Sleng genocide Museum - a mass gravesite and a former high school converted to a detention and torture centre by the Khmers Rouges when they came to power in 1975. We will have a free afternoon and you can relax at hotel or explore Royal Palace and Russian Market. Meals: B, D</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 8: End of tour</strong></p>\r\n<p>The tour end after breakfast, you will have free time to explore central town or relax at the hotel before flight out. There are international flights to Bangkok or Vietnam and many other Asian destinations. Meals: B<strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Service included:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Accommodation twin share basis with daily breakfast and all kind of tax</p>\r\n<p>An experienced English-speaking local guide</p>\r\n<p>All ground transportation as mention on the itinerary</p>\r\n<p>Sightseeing fee during guiding</p>\r\n<p>Meals as stated on the itinerary (B: Breakfast, L: Lunch, D: Dinner)</p>\r\n<p>Boat trip Kep and Sihanoukville</p>\r\n<p>Water during the tours</p>\r\n<p><strong>Service excluded:</strong></p>\r\n<p>All airfare, airport taxes and excess baggage charges</p>\r\n<p>All kind of own expenses</p>\r\n<p>Visa, Visa fee and vaccination charges</p>\r\n<p>Departure tax (25$)</p>\r\n<p>Personal travel insurance (compulsory)</p>\r\n<p>All optional tours &amp; activities during free time</p>\r\n<p>All beverages during the included meals</p>\r\n<p>Expenditure of a personal nature, such as souvenir, laundry, postage, phone calls</p>\r\n<p>Tips</p>', null);
